1
00:00:01,768 --> 00:00:18,782
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:19,132 --> 00:00:26,864
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa.

3
00:00:27,605 --> 00:00:31,910
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:34,052 --> 00:00:40,762
So I thought this evening I'd tackle this thorny problem of social karma.

5
00:00:44,406 --> 00:00:47,030
Now, according to the Buddha,

6
00:00:47,719 --> 00:00:52,485
The karma that we own is the actions that we've performed.

7
00:00:53,046 --> 00:00:56,210
So these can be a thought, speech or, of course, actions.

8
00:00:57,512 --> 00:01:00,517
And they're all products of the will.

9
00:01:00,676 --> 00:01:03,201
It's the will that manifests them.

10
00:01:06,305 --> 00:01:07,787
Now, some of these are automatic.

11
00:01:08,126 --> 00:01:11,671
You know, we're just habitually thinking, doing things.

12
00:01:13,093 --> 00:01:17,118
Speech, of course, tends to be spontaneous or unfortunately impulsive.

13
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:32,701
But then there are times when our responses are measured, when we have to think about what we're going to do, and those have often the greatest force within our personality.

14
00:01:36,828 --> 00:01:45,503
And the importance in the process of liberation is the ethical value, or lack of it, of course.

15
00:01:46,546 --> 00:01:57,983
So these mental states, these sankara, are created by our decisions, moment-to-moment decisions, moment-after-moment, whether they are habitual or considered.

16
00:02:01,888 --> 00:02:08,479
Now, from that, it might be a little bit confusing to talk about social karma.

17
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:11,623
I think it's better to talk about social conditioning.

18
00:02:11,944 --> 00:02:13,347
That makes a bit more sense, I think.

19
00:02:15,688 --> 00:02:42,033
the fact is that we're embedded in our culture um i was visiting my brother down in the isle of wight and i was just watching this grandfather and grandmother taking their grandchild for a walk and the child sort of stopped and turned around and lifting her arms to the air was obviously asking her grandfather to lift her up and he kept and i could hear him saying

20
00:02:42,401 --> 00:03:00,799
uh and so she she'd probably saying lift me up and he'd say and this this went on for a little while unfortunately my attention was taken away uh and of course uh i presume his uh the grandmother was um

21
00:03:01,014 --> 00:03:30,701
uh cut in just uh you know unable to bear uh the husband's unwillingness to response to the child's please and prompted her by saying that magic word please so so right there he took it upon himself to teach the child that you have to say please and usually of course as children we we totally accept the conditioning

22
00:03:30,951 --> 00:03:38,923
It's only when we get to be naughty teenagers and later in life when we can reflect that we can see the conditioning that we have.

23
00:03:41,045 --> 00:03:44,891
We also, of course, pick up our prejudices.

24
00:03:45,973 --> 00:03:49,698
So I remember my niece and nephew were playing hospital.

25
00:03:51,060 --> 00:03:58,090
And my nephew was two years older than my niece, but they were both under seven, six and four.

26
00:03:58,153 --> 00:04:02,237
And of course, he said, I'll be the doctor and you'll be the nurse.

27
00:04:04,039 --> 00:04:09,444
And afterwards, I thought to myself, if she'd been the elder, would she have chosen to be the doctor?

28
00:04:11,907 --> 00:04:14,308
The same is true, of course, of racial prejudice.

29
00:04:16,271 --> 00:04:19,134
I was traveling to get back home.

30
00:04:20,055 --> 00:04:25,680
I had to go from Liverpool Street to Waterloo, and it really is a pain.

31
00:04:26,403 --> 00:04:29,507
And unfortunately, I ended up in Canary Wharf thinking it'd be easier.

32
00:04:30,488 --> 00:04:34,535
And I hadn't a clue where I was and everybody said I should take the Jubilee line.

33
00:04:34,995 --> 00:04:38,821
So I was really stuck and everybody sort of disappeared apart from this black guy.

34
00:04:39,802 --> 00:04:42,505
So I asked him, you see, you know, how to get there.

35
00:04:43,247 --> 00:04:50,858
Now, as I asked him, I could feel this sort of anxiety that he might

36
00:04:51,343 --> 00:05:16,372
reject my request in some way on the understanding on my understanding how he feels about white people i mean i was lucky he happened to be working near the jubilee line which was something like a 15-minute walk away through so i don't know how many streets and he was very glad to take me but i was interested in my

37
00:05:16,959 --> 00:05:45,228
in my the men in in that idea that came up as i was asking him i actually got out of my way to ask people of color uh yeah so uh the other one of course another one is you know we just celebrated the queen's platinum jubilee and uh it's no doubt that she's been she's you know she's fulfilled that role of the monarch admirably

38
00:05:46,036 --> 00:05:49,040
But have we ever actually considered the institution of monarchy?

39
00:05:49,579 --> 00:05:53,644
Now, I have to confess, I am a lifelong Republican.

40
00:05:56,588 --> 00:06:00,793
You have to forgive me for that.

41
00:06:00,814 --> 00:06:07,622
And that, of course, the monarchy, the institution, is the preserve of nobility, of privilege, the house of laws and all that.

42
00:06:07,641 --> 00:06:10,625
And it has an influence on us.

43
00:06:10,646 --> 00:06:14,170
It has an influence of how we see ourselves in society.

44
00:06:14,622 --> 00:06:16,124
How would you feel if you met her?

45
00:06:20,348 --> 00:06:30,057
Then, of course, something I've been banging on about these past couple of weeks is neoliberal, the neoliberal ideology, and what it's done to us, made us much more selfish.

46
00:06:31,980 --> 00:06:41,389
So, for instance, in the NHS, instead of being patients, we were told that we were clients.

47
00:06:43,107 --> 00:06:50,423
And this meant that we moved away from an attitude of gratitude to entitlement.

48
00:06:50,442 --> 00:06:54,672
And the amount of suing of the NHS went up enormously.

49
00:06:55,394 --> 00:07:00,524
And it stands today at, yes, last year at £2.4 billion.

50
00:07:01,432 --> 00:07:08,620
Now, it's not that we shouldn't be compensated for poor treatment.

51
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:09,961
That's not the problem.

52
00:07:10,603 --> 00:07:18,471
It's just where we're coming from, the indignant entitled as opposed to the injured patient.

53
00:07:19,552 --> 00:07:25,500
So how do you feel when you go for a service, when the bus doesn't arrive?

54
00:07:26,461 --> 00:07:30,444
My parents would have just felt grateful.

55
00:07:31,588 --> 00:07:36,776
There's even now, I don't know whether you know about this, a defensive dentistry.

56
00:07:37,257 --> 00:07:42,947
Dentists won't do anything on your teeth unless they have proof there's something wrong.

57
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:50,639
They're absolutely scared of being sued for anything they do.

58
00:07:51,141 --> 00:07:54,146
There have been some really bad cases because of that.

59
00:07:56,088 --> 00:07:58,692
At a deeper level, of course, it's our race.

60
00:07:59,752 --> 00:08:00,713
How do we feel?

61
00:08:01,875 --> 00:08:07,221
You know, if we're black, how do we feel being in a white-dominated culture?

62
00:08:07,641 --> 00:08:11,766
Jews' unrelenting history of persecution.

63
00:08:13,129 --> 00:08:29,288
And then there's, of course, whites who are, at the moment, are being, shall we say, suggested by extreme Brexiteers with their shining luminary Boris that projects us as British, special, etc., etc.,

64
00:08:32,018 --> 00:08:36,677
So all this will be there within us.

65
00:08:37,160 --> 00:08:42,062
I mean, I came across real prejudice, shall we say, when I became a monk.

66
00:08:42,937 --> 00:09:07,071
uh one one time i walked into a shop and the assistant or the shopkeeper simply turned around and walked out i was left just standing there until i realized she wasn't going to come out to serve me and then there was a quite nasty occasion when i was at dubai so i was flying back from sri lanka when this drunken englishman just went on and on about how stupid and ridiculous i looked

67
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:22,100
So it's catching how our personal conditioning, not the societal conditioning, how we are personally conditioned.

68
00:09:25,505 --> 00:09:32,134
And although we've had little choice in that conditioning, the fact of the matter is, it's us.

69
00:09:32,895 --> 00:09:39,825
We are an expression of our culture, and it's our duty, it's our responsibility to accept that,

70
00:09:40,143 --> 00:09:42,548
and to do something about it when it's unwholesome.

71
00:09:44,451 --> 00:09:52,067
I mean, I have stressed the unwholesomeness within society, but obviously there's beauty too.

72
00:09:52,147 --> 00:09:58,219
And just mentioning the NHS, it's a product of a society of care.

73
00:10:01,472 --> 00:10:07,899
So everything around us is influencing us, and we are influencing everybody around us.

74
00:10:08,360 --> 00:10:15,467
So there's a certain responsibility there to make sure we know where we stand with all these issues.

75
00:10:17,169 --> 00:10:29,623
I mean, the Buddha has lots of advice for laypeople in the Sigalavada Sutta, where he talks in detail about your relationship within a family.

76
00:10:29,772 --> 00:10:34,057
It's of course very patriarchal, but then he was a man of his time.

77
00:10:36,701 --> 00:10:51,700
And the monks were allowed to wander any way they wished, but during the rainy season they had to come together and re-establish the fact that they were a community.

78
00:10:52,120 --> 00:10:59,070
And of course he goes on to say how good companionship is the whole of the spiritual life.

79
00:10:59,606 --> 00:11:04,852
I mean, Ananda has come to the opinion that it's only half the holy life.

80
00:11:04,873 --> 00:11:08,716
And the Buddha replies, don't say that, Ananda, don't say that.

81
00:11:10,259 --> 00:11:17,527
Admirable friendship, admirable companionship, admirable camaraderie is actually the whole of the spiritual life.

82
00:11:18,347 --> 00:11:27,217
When a monk has admirable friends, people as friends, companions and comrades, he can be expected to develop and pursue the Noble Eightfold Path.

83
00:11:29,357 --> 00:11:32,009
And of course, he has also

84
00:11:32,799 --> 00:11:59,802
advice that he gave really to the Duddaba who wanted to attack the Vajji Confederacy, pointing out that the nation's welfare was dependent on frequent meetings, that assemblies assemble and disperse peacefully and attend to their affairs in concord, that they do not enact new decrees or abolish old ones,

85
00:11:59,850 --> 00:12:03,355
and proceed in accordance with ancient constitutions.

86
00:12:08,524 --> 00:12:24,407
They respect, honour and esteem their elders, refrain from abducting women and maidens of good families, show respect, honour and esteem and veneration to shrines, and look after their arahats.

87
00:12:24,471 --> 00:12:30,221
So, of course, you can retranslate that for our own times.

88
00:12:31,361 --> 00:12:41,197
But here the Buddha is actually saying that the society we are in, we are dependent on it for our conditioning.

89
00:12:41,778 --> 00:12:43,259
We are responsible.

90
00:12:43,299 --> 00:12:49,389
Once we know we're conditioned, once we know our conditioning, we are responsible for it.

91
00:12:50,309 --> 00:12:51,491
And where we can,

92
00:12:51,741 --> 00:12:54,465
we develop a right conditioning.

93
00:12:54,884 --> 00:12:57,287
And in so doing, we affect the people around us.

94
00:12:58,948 --> 00:13:04,014
So that's about as far as I think social conditioning goes.

95
00:13:04,073 --> 00:13:06,796
So we can't really talk about social karma.

96
00:13:07,236 --> 00:13:21,309
We can only talk about our social conditioning within ourselves and then how we work with it, how we deal with it, and hopefully clear our hearts of anything that's negative.

97
00:13:23,956 --> 00:13:35,993
So I don't know whether that's created more confusion or in some way brightened up this little dark area, which I don't think many people talk about.

98
00:13:37,193 --> 00:13:51,955
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that you will, by your endeavor to overcome all negative social conditioning, arise into the glory of Arahatship sooner rather than later.

